{
  "doc_id": "7340",
  "text": "In 2006, the first successful percutaneous implantation of a commercially available centrifugal flow pump* as a TandemHeart-right ventricular support device (CF-RVSD) was reported [CITATION_1] . Since then, CF-RVSDs have been implanted for RVF in the settings of AMI [CITATION_2] , after left ventricular (LV) AD surgery [CITATION_3] , severe pulmonary hypertension [CITATION_4] , and cardiac rejection after orthotopic heart transplantation [CITATION_5] . Unlike conventional therapy for RVF with the intra-aortic balloon pump (IABP), the CF-RVSD provides flow from the right atrium (RA) to the main pulmonary artery (PA), thereby bypassing a poorly functioning RV [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Limited data on the clinical utility of the CF-RVSD exist [CITATION_8] . The aim of this study was to explore the hemodynamic effects and clinical outcomes associated with use of the CF-RVSD for RVF in clinical practice.",
